Business Analysis - Task 2 - Question 2 - Exploratory Analysis

In the following documents we will run and train a series of Machine Learning models with the aim of finding relations between our process dataset. The content of the present work is as follows:

  • Data pre-processing
    • Flattening of the data
    • Converting NaN into useful values (applying assumptions)
  • Exploratory Data Analysis with Descriptive Statistics and Machine Learning
    • Unsupervised Learning with K-Means
    • Supervised Learning with K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)
    • Deep Learning (Supervised Learning) Convolutional Neural Networks (CNN)
  • Findings and conclusions

First, we need to run the necessary libraries including os (for operating system related tasks), pandas (for handling data in tables called dataframes), numpy (for handling data in 2D and 3D arrays), sklearn (for preprocessing of data as well as training and prediciting with machine learning models) and matplotlib (for data and model visualisation)

After checking the data we discovered the following redundancies:

  • Plan A referes to the Insurance of EUR 25000 and Plan B to the Insurance of EUR 120000, the column plan is redudant.
  • Each case belongs to a unique client, assuming -EMPTY- are different individuals. Even in the few homonym cases, the subjects have different age. We assume that the columns first_name and last_name are considered unnecesary for this analysis.
  • ...(Redundancy 3 placeholder)

Our goal at this point is to get the following information regarding the major decision points for each case ID:

  • The basic check failing or not
  • The type of application check performed (high or low), and
  • The ultimate outcome after the check is performed (accept or reject)
In order to achieve this goal with create lists with the corresponding positional value for each Case ID.

In [158]:
case_ids = df["Case ID"].tolist()
creditscores = df["creditscore"].fillna(False).tolist()
basic_checks = list() #1 if True (fails), 0 if False (basic check succeeds) #"Initiate Low Application Check" #
app_check_type = list()
cscores = list()
pscores = list()
for rang in range(1+max(df["Case ID"].tolist())):
    max_creditscore=max(df[df["Case ID"]==rang].fillna(-20)["creditscore"].tolist())
    max_p_score=max(df[df["Case ID"]==rang].fillna(-20)["net_promotor_score"].tolist())
    activities = df[df["Case ID"]==rang]["Activity"].tolist()
    cscores.append(max_creditscore)
    pscores.append(max_p_score)
    if "Basic Check Succeeded" in activities:
        basic_checks.append("Succeeded")
    elif "Basic Check Skipped" in activities:
        basic_checks.append("Skipped") # Could be merged with succeeded
    elif "Basic Check Failed" in activities:
        basic_checks.append("Failed")
    else:
        basic_checks.append("None")#theres no other case, this is just a placeholder
    if "Initiate Low Application Check" in activities:
        app_check_type.append("Low")
    elif "Initiate High Application Check" in activities:
        app_check_type.append("High")
    else:
        app_check_type.append("None")

Now that we have the major decision points ready, we flatten the data to a single row per Case ID, we name this new DataFrame df_flat

In order to achieve this we did the following steps with their associated assumptions:

  • Drop all the rows except from the first (when Activity=="Registration" or Age!=NaN) for each Case ID
  • Drop the columns we consider redundant, unnecesary and/or problematic in the Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Extract the outcomes (accept or reject) from the original DataFrame and place them in the new flatten DataFrame

cases_df = df.dropna(subset = ["age"])#removing all rows except from the first row of each Case ID
cases_df["age"].replace("-EMPTY-", -20, inplace=True)#We use-20 to highlght missing age with regular age in the visualization
cases_df.loc[:,"Start Day"] = [ele.day_of_week for ele in cases_df["Start Timestamp"]]#use .day_name() for string output
cases_df.drop(["Case ID","Activity", "Resource", "Start Timestamp","Complete Timestamp","first_name", "last_name", "plan","result","stopcode"], axis=1,inplace=True)
cases_df.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
cases_df.loc[:,"basic_check"]=basic_checks
cases_df.loc[:,"application_check"]=app_check_type
cases_df.loc[:,"net_promotor_score"]=pscores
cases_df.loc[:,"creditscore"]=cscores
cases_df["outcome"]=df.dropna(subset=["outcome"])["outcome"].reset_index(drop=True)
cases_df["outcome"].replace({"accept":1, "reject":0}, inplace=True)#accept= 1
cases_df["rate_charged"]=df.dropna(subset=["outcome"])["rate_charged"].fillna(-20).reset_index(drop=True)#we assume there is no charged if failed
for col_t in cases_df.columns:#transforming floats to integers to give same importance to continues features
    if str(cases_df[col_t].dtype)=="float64":
        cases_df[col_t] = cases_df[col_t].astype('int64')

for col1 in cases_df.columns:
    for col2 in cases_df.columns:
        if col1!=col2 and [col1, col2] not in unique_f_pairs and [col2, col1] not in unique_f_pairs:
            unique_f_pairs.append([col1, col2])

Unsupervised Learning with K-Means

We are going to apply an the Elbow method to get the optimal number of clusters (k), plotting both the Elbow method (K vs sum of squarred distances) and KMeans clusters

...

In [179]:
for col1, col2 in unique_f_pairs:
    #print()
    k_df = cases_df[[col1, col2]]
    if str(k_df[col1].dtype)=="object":
        le1 = preprocessing.LabelEncoder()
        le1.fit(k_df[col1])
        k_df[col1] = le1.transform(k_df[col1])
    if str(k_df[col2].dtype)=="object":
        le2 = preprocessing.LabelEncoder()
        le2.fit(k_df[col2])
        k_df[col2] = le2.transform(k_df[col2])
    k_df = k_df[(k_df[col1]>=0) & (k_df[col2]>=0)]#testing only positive values####
    Sum_of_squared_distances = list()
    silhouette_scores = list()
    K = range(2,12)
    for k in K:
        km = KMeans(n_clusters=k)
        km = km.fit(k_df)
        Sum_of_squared_distances.append(km.inertia_)
        s_labels = KMeans(n_clusters=k, init="k-means++").fit(k_df).labels_
        silhouette_scores.append(metrics.silhouette_score(k_df, labels=s_labels, metric="euclidean"))
    plt.plot(K, Sum_of_squared_distances, 'bx-')
    plt.xlabel('k')
    plt.ylabel('Sum_of_squared_distances')
    plt.title(f"Elbow Method For Optimal k - {col1.upper()} and {col2.upper()}")
    plt.show()
    o_k_index=silhouette_scores.index(max(silhouette_scores))
    optimal_k = K[o_k_index]
    optimal_s_c = silhouette_scores[o_k_index]
    print(f"According to the silhoutte score, the best number of clusters for {col1.upper()} and {col2.upper()} is {optimal_k}")
    km_optimal=KMeans(n_clusters=optimal_k, init="k-means++")
    km_optimal.fit(k_df)
    plt.scatter(k_df[col1], k_df[col2], c=km_optimal.labels_.astype(float), )
    plt.title(f"K-Means Clustering with {col1.upper()} and {col2.upper()}")
    plt.xlabel(col1)
    plt.ylabel(col2)
    plt.show()

Findings

In the present section we try to solve the following questions:

  • When do you see a basic check failing or a registration being rejected?In other words, to which attribute(s) can this be linked? How often does this happen?
  • When do you see a high versus low application check?How often do you observe the “initiate a low application check”? And how often a high check? What is the decision logic to decide which type of check to follow?
  • Which attributes have a causal effect on rejection? What are the different reasons for a case to be rejected?
  • Can you figure out whether the company follows a set of strict conditions (based on different attributes and results from checks)
  • Which lead to the case being rejected?
  • Do you see some other decision points or data variables that could be investigated? Can every customer freely decide on taking ‘plan A’ or ‘plan B’?*We already found that Plan A is tied to the Coverage*
